{{refimprove|date=July 2009}}
'''Bislish'''  is a [[portmanteau]] of the words ''[[Visayan languages|Bisaya]]'' and ''[[Philippine English|English]]'', which refers to any of the [[Visayan languages]] of the [[Languages of the Philippines|Philippines]] [[Macaronic language|macaronically]] infused with [[Philippine English|English]] terms. It is an example of [[code mixing]]. An example of Bislish as spoken in [[Cebuano language|Cebuano]]-speaking areas would be, "Tired na jud<ref name="gyud pronunciation">''Gyud'' is pronounced as either {{IPA|[dʒud]}}, {{IPA|[ɡjud]}}, or {{IPA|[ɡud]}}. In informal communications, it is also occasionally written as ''g&#146;ud'' (often ''gud'' or ''jud'')</ref> ko my friend, how far pa house nimo?" which means "I am so tired already my friend. How far is your house?". Another example in [[Hiligaynon language|Hiligaynon]]-speaking areas is "Lagaw kita at the park, magkit-anay ta sa friends naton didto.", which means "Let's stroll at the park, we'll meet our friends there."

